In TeXstudio, `\maketitle` is not a “shortcut” or a TeXstudio-specific command; it is a standard LaTeX macro.  
Its purpose is to typeset the previously defined title, author, and date—set via `\title{...}`, `\author{...}`, and `\date{...}`—into a title page.  
As long as the document class is one of the standard ones like `article`, `report`, `book`, or any class that inherits from them, `\maketitle` will work.

In TeXstudio you only need to make sure that:  
1. the document starts with `\documentclass{...}`;  
2. `\maketitle` appears after `\begin{document}` (usually right after it);  
3. you have already filled in `\title{}`, `\author{}`, and `\date{}` before that point.

Example:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\title{My Paper}
\author{John Doe}
\date{\today}

\begin{document}
\maketitle           % produces title, author, and date here

\section{Introduction}
Text begins...
\end{document}
```

Thus, `\maketitle` means exactly the same in TeXstudio as in any other LaTeX editor—it is simply the command that generates the title page.

